On #ThisDayInHistory in 1788, Georgia ratified the U.S. Constitution, becoming the fourth state and first southern state to join the Union. 

Settled in 1733 by British debtors under James Oglethorpe, the colony was named after King George II. It prospered due to its fertile land and export potential. During the Revolutionary War, Georgia was divided between Loyalists and Patriots, with British forces eventually occupying most of the state. Savannah became a key British base, but the occupation helped shift public sentiment toward the Patriot cause.

Name: Meuser, Daniel
text:
President Biden‚Äôs decision to award members of the January 6th Committee the second-highest civilian medal is an affront to the truth and to the American people. The January 6th Committee was a sham‚Äîa kangaroo court with a predetermined outcome: find President Trump guilty. They blocked Republican members from joining the committee who would have sought fairness, proving it was never about uncovering the truth but about advancing a partisan agenda at the expense of taxpayers.
¬†
On January 6th, Speaker Nancy Pelosi admitted on camera that she was ‚Äúresponsible‚Äù for the security failures, including her refusal to call for the National Guard despite serious warnings. Yet, the committee ignored these facts entirely. Instead, they withheld or deleted crucial records, failing to archive more than a terabyte of data‚Äîequivalent to 6.5 million pages of documents‚Äîand destroyed video recordings of witness interviews, which is against House Rules, while selectively editing clips for public hearings that fit their narrative. This charade wasted taxpayer dollars and obstructed genuine efforts to understand and address the failures of that day.
¬†
Giving an award to the architects of this farce insults the American people and undermines justice. Anyone accepting this so-called recognition becomes part of the charade. This fits a disturbing pattern from this administration‚Äîpardoning felon family members, excusing corrupt deals, and now rewarding political theater. Americans deserve better than this disgraceful spectacle.
¬†
Thankfully, on January 20th, we will move past this backward, divisive ideology. America deserves leadership that prioritizes truth, accountability, and justice‚Äînot partisan vendettas.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we celebrate the stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district, individuals whose actions transform lives and leave a lasting mark on our community. Today, we honor an extraordinary woman whose unwavering compassion and commitment are a testament to the power of one person‚Äôs determination to change the world‚Äîmeet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero, Fran Held, of Lansdale.

From an early age, Fran was drawn to helping others‚Äîworking tirelessly to address homelessness, poverty, and food insecurity wherever she could. For years, she served without fanfare or recognition, simply answering the call of those in need. But one day, Fran received a phone call that changed everything.

The voice on the other end said, ‚ÄúI heard you‚Äôre the lady who will help me when no one else will.‚Äù In that moment, Fran realized her calling was not just a passion but a mission. She understood then that although she didn‚Äôt have vast financial resources, she had something even more powerful‚Äîa heart willing to act.

In 2009, Fran turned compassion into action by founding Mitzvah Circle, a nonprofit dedicated to restoring dignity and hope for families facing extraordinary hardships.

Today, Mitzvah Circle serves over 73,000 families annually, distributing 4.5 million essential items‚Äîincluding 3 million diapers‚Äîto address urgent needs. With 1 in 3 American families unable to afford diapers, the organization provides critical supplies like wipes and baby essentials to protect children‚Äôs health and help parents return to work.

But Mitzvah Circle goes further, offering over 100 necessities‚Äîclothing, school supplies, toiletries‚Äîproviding essential support and empowering families to regain stability and build brighter futures.

In addition, their Teen Ambassador Program provides an invaluable opportunity for high school students to make a meaningful impact while cultivating essential leadership skills that will serve them, our community, and country for a lifetime.

Mitzvah Circle‚Äôs impact is a community effort, with partnerships spanning nearly 300 organizations and the dedication of more than 4,200 volunteers each year. From churches and synagogues to mosques and civic groups, Fran has worked to build bridges that unite people across faiths and backgrounds in the common mission of kindness and care. In Fran‚Äôs words, ‚ÄúYou don‚Äôt have to change your entire life to make an impact. One act of kindness can change everything for someone.‚Äù

Fran‚Äôs unwavering dedication has built a brighter future for thousands. She has shown us that compassion is the cornerstone of a strong community, and her leadership continues to inspire us to build a better world‚Äîone act of kindness at a time.

Join me in applauding Fran, a true Hometown Hero.

Name: Johnson, Mike
text:
The American people¬†have demanded an end to the status quo, and a return to fiscal sanity.¬†That‚Äôs why the citizens of our great country gave President Trump the White House and Republican control of both chambers of Congress.¬†If we don‚Äôt follow through on our campaign promise for fiscal responsibility, we don‚Äôt deserve to hold power.¬† The national debt is a grave threat to America‚Äôs economic and national security ‚Äì and no issue exemplifies the Congress‚Äô failures more. ¬† 

Republicans have a real opportunity in the next two years to make meaningful spending reforms to eliminate trillions in waste, fraud, and abuse, and end the weaponization of government.¬† Along with advancing President Trump‚Äôs America First agenda, I will lead the House Republicans to reduce the size and scope of the federal government, hold the bureaucracy accountable, and move the United States to a more sustainable fiscal trajectory. ¬† 

As Speaker, I commit to: 

1. Create a working group comprised of independent experts ‚Äì not corrupted by lobbyists and special interests ‚Äì to work with DOGE¬†and our committees¬†on implementing recommended government and spending reforms to protect the American taxpayer. 

2. Task that working group with reviewing existing audits of federal agencies and entities created by Congress ‚Äì and issuing a report to my office for public release. 

3. Request¬†House committees undertake aggressive authorizations and appropriations reviews, including providing additional resources where needed, to expose irresponsible or illegal practices and hold agencies/individuals accountable that have weaponized government against the American people. ¬† 

If we want to¬†restore¬†fiscal responsibility, we must start by being transparent about the dollars that are spent, address the issues we find, and then hold those accountable who have misspent funds. Republicans have a mandate to implement the America First Agenda, and as Speaker, this will be¬†my priority.

Name: Meuser, Daniel
text:
President Biden‚Äôs decision to block the U.S. Steel-Nippon Steel Deal is a significant blow to Pennsylvania and the American steel industry. This $14.9 billion investment would have made U.S. Steel the largest producer in America, created nearly 6,000 new jobs, and modernized plants with $2.7 billion in cutting-edge upgrades‚Äîall while keeping production in Pennsylvania. Japan is a trusted ally, not an adversary like China.

Our hope and expectation is President Trump will step in, review this investment in a business-minded way as only he can, and hopefully save U.S. Steel while making it better for America. Revitalizing industries, securing jobs, and protecting American workers is his specialty, and much of Pennsylvania‚Äôs steel manufacturing future is at stake. We hope President Trump can save U.S. Steel for the second time and have Japan pay for it.

Read my full thoughts below:
https://t.co/CcqbVJ2Dhx

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First

Alexis Davis resides in Edenton and served as a dedicated veteran employment representative. He provides crucial job placement assistance, community resource referrals, and services to veterans, the disabled, the elderly, and qualifying spouses. He also leads initiatives to provide meals, groceries, and clothing to veterans in need through donations from local community partners.

His volunteer work has profoundly impacted the Northeastern North Carolina community. He has become a dependable resource for veterans, offering personal healthcare services, home clean-up assistance, and food delivery in times of critical need. Whether it‚Äôs helping seasoned veterans access necessary benefits, supporting transitioning service members from out of state, or guiding military spouses toward education and employment opportunities, Alexis is committed to meeting the needs of those who served.

In recognition of his outstanding service, Alexis was honored as the Consolidated Veterans Employment Consultant of the Year 2023. His dedication to the veteran community and his unwavering service make a significant difference in the lives of many in the region.

#FridaySpotlight

Arkansas‚Äôs First Congressional District produces more steel than any other district in America. The U.S. Steel-Nippon Steel proposed merger would have been an economic boon to my district and to dozens more around the country with a U.S. Steel presence. While the thousands of steel workers in Mississippi County, Arkansas, will continue producing the highest quality, cleanest steel that the world has come to expect from our top-notch factories, I am saddened that politics got in the way of greater investments today. Our national steel-making industry could have been strengthened by this merger. Instead, we must look to the future and hope U.S. Steel can find a way to renew this partnership with our Japanese allies and continue investing in America. One thing I know for certain: Arkansans are ready to make more steel!

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1847, Samuel Colt secured a crucial contract to supply 1,000 .44 caliber revolvers to the government, saving his struggling gun company.

Before Colt's mass production of revolvers, handguns were rare and impractical, often expensive, inaccurate, and preferred mostly by elites for formal duels. The average American, especially in the West, favored knives for self-defense. This changed with Colt's invention of the percussion-repeating revolver, which featured a revolving chamber holding multiple shots, making it more practical for quick combat. While not as accurate as rifles, the revolver's rapid-fire ability made up for this shortcoming.

Colt's early success was fueled by government contracts, which allowed him to scale production. Colt developed mass production techniques, reducing costs and making revolvers more affordable. Colt‚Äôs guns became popular during the California Gold Rush, and by 1860, he had sold over 268,000 revolvers, largely to civilians seeking self-defense in the Wild West.

(01:49) Motivation to Serve
(02:53) Joining the Army
(04:38) The Military Recruiting Crisis
(05:53) Afghanistan Withdrawal
(08:52) Running for Polk County Sheriff
(10:07) Running for State Legislature
(10:55) Elected Lieutenant Governor
(11:55) Becoming Governor: Discovering, Facing Challenges, and the Call to Serve
(15:13) Greatest Accomplishment as Governor
(17:17) Toughest Decisions as Governor
++ much more! 

In this episode of Mark Alford's America, Congressman Mark Alford sits down with Missouri‚Äôs 57th Governor, Mike Parson, at his Kansas City office. Governor Parson reflects on a lifetime of service, from his days in the U.S. Army to serving as Polk County Sheriff, and his path to the Governor‚Äôs office.

He shares insights on the values driving his leadership, his commitment to Missouri‚Äôs infrastructure and workforce development, and his dedication to creating opportunities for future generations. Governor Parson also shares the inside story of how he found out he would become governor and what those first few days were like. 

Tune in for an inspiring conversation with@GovParsonMO!

Originally aired: Nov 2, 2024

I am honored to have been elected to represent the people of Florida‚Äôs 26th Congressional District. Name: Fletcher, Lizzie
text: It has been 4 years since the violent attack on our Capitol as Congress met to certify the 2020 election results. Today, I'm grateful to the @CapitolPolice, @DCPoliceDept, & others who put their lives on the line to protect Congress, the Capitol, the Constitution, & the country.

Name: Fletcher, Lizzie
text: I was inside the Capitol that day, in the Gallery of the House Chamber. I saw and heard the people storming the Capitol. Through the third-floor window, I saw mobs on the steps. As I escaped the Gallery later, I saw them inside the Capitol hallways.

Name: Fletcher, Lizzie
text: Our law enforcement officers and others who work throughout the Capitol‚Äîfrom House clerks to janitorial staff‚Äîworked tirelessly, through danger and distress, to make it possible for Congress to come back to the Capitol and vote to certify the election later that day. And we did.

Name: Fletcher, Lizzie
text: It was a dark and sad day for our country. Yet, in the years since, many people have sought to minimize and dismiss this attack on our country and our democracy. Just this morning, I heard news stories with Americans saying they thought it didn't even really happen.

Name: Fletcher, Lizzie
text: I relied on the U.S. Capitol Police to protect me personally and to protect the Congress broadly. And they did, providing protection and calm guidance for those of us trapped inside, fighting the mobs inside and outside the entire Capitol.

Name: Fletcher, Lizzie
text: It did. I was there. I witnessed it. And people at home and across the country witnessed it, too‚Äîthanks to the reporters inside and outside the Capitol who reported in real time what was happening there, also at great personal risk.

Name: Fletcher, Lizzie
text: I am deeply concerned about this dismissive, dangerous narrative that has emerged about that day. We cannot forget the irresponsible rhetoric and blatant lies that brought people to the Capitol that day.

Name: Fletcher, Lizzie
text: And we must not forget the heroism of the U.S. Capitol Police and other law enforcement officers who fought for America and all Americans that day. We owe them a debt of gratitude we can never fully repay.

Name: Fletcher, Lizzie
text: Later today, Congress will convene to certify the 2024 election results. We are able to do so because of the courage and determination of those who have fought for our American democracy for nearly 250 years, including on January 6, 2021, a day we must never forget.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text:
Exciting News for the Coastal Bend!

I‚Äôm grateful to share that the bill I introduced to name the U.S. post office in downtown Corpus Christi after one of our community's most remarkable heroes, Captain Robert E. ‚ÄòBob‚Äô Batterson, was signed into law by the President‚Äîensuring his legacy of service and sacrifice will be remembered for generations to come.

Captain Robert E. ‚ÄòBob‚Äô Batterson was a true American hero who dedicated 35 years of his life to serving our nation in the U.S. Navy. His remarkable career began when he enlisted in 1939 and included being stationed at Pearl Harbor during the attack on December 7, 1941‚Äîone of the most pivotal moments in American history. Following that, he earned his wings at Naval Air Station Corpus Christi and served as a Navy Aviator during World War II, piloting F6F Hellcats in defense of our nation. After the war, he transitioned to the Navy‚Äôs Supply Corps, continuing his service until retiring in 1974.

In retirement, he remained deeply committed to serving his community, spending 26 years volunteering at the U.S.S. Lexington Museum in Corpus Christi. His dedication inspired visitors from near and far, especially at the Pearl Harbor exhibit, where he preserved the memory of those who served and sacrificed for our freedoms. Captain Batterson‚Äôs life exemplified service, sacrifice, and a love for his country and community. Naming this post office after him ensures his legacy will live on for generations.

May his story continue to inspire us all who walk through its doors, and may God bless the Batterson family. üá∫üá∏

Name: Pelosi, Nancy
text:
Four years ago today, our nation watched in horror as a terrorist mob stormed the Capitol grounds and desecrated our Temple of Democracy in a violent attempt to subvert the peaceful transfer of power.¬† 

The January 6th insurrection shook our Republic to its core ‚Äî and left behind physical scars and emotional trauma on members of our Congressional community and our Country that endure to this day.¬†

We must never forget the extraordinary courage of law enforcement officers on January 6th who stood in the breach and stared down the insurrectionists to protect the Capitol, the Congress and the Constitution.¬† 

We are forever grateful to these heroes whose valor ensured that democracy survived on that dark day ‚Äî and we continue to pray for the fallen, the afflicted and their families.

The parable of January 6th reminds us that our precious democratic institutions are only as strong as the courage and commitment of those entrusted with their care.¬† 

On January 6th, we gave proof through the night that our Flag was still there by returning to the Capitol to certify the election results and demonstrate to America and the world that our Democracy prevailed.¬†¬†
¬†
As we gather today under President Lincoln‚Äôs dome to uphold our oath and peacefully certify the will of the people, we all share a responsibility to preserve American democracy ‚Äî which Lincoln called, ‚Äúthe last best hope of earth.‚Äù

I was sworn in to the 119th Congress on Friday, and I want to thank #WA03 for entrusting me to continue serving as an independent voice for our communities' priorities.

For two years, I've brought dollars home for overdue investments in our infrastructure, passed bipartisan bills to keep our woods working and support rural development, and cut through red tape to bring back $5.5 million owed to you by federal agencies.

But there‚Äôs more urgent work to be done.

As our communities endure a high cost of living, the devastation of fentanyl, and the demands of aging infrastructure, I'm hitting the ground running this Congress to find bipartisan solutions.

No party has a monopoly on good ideas, so I look forward to rising above clickbait politics and putting Southwest Washington's needs ahead of the D.C. agenda.

I don‚Äôt take this responsibility lightly, so I hope you‚Äôll stay in touch about the issues that matter most to you, and I‚Äôll continue to do the same.

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text:
Earlier today, President Biden signed two memoranda withdrawing a total of 625 million acres of the federal Outer Continental Shelf‚Äîincluding the entire East Coast, the West Coast, the Eastern Gulf of Mexico, and tens of millions more acres off of Alaska‚Äîfrom potential oil and gas development.

I have long agreed that not all offshore areas need to be available for development at all times, and that some areas merit more permanent protections. I also understand the desire of Alaska Tribes in the Bering Straits region to prevent any oil and gas development in their nearby waters, as unlikely as that may be.

Still, my objection to the President‚Äôs actions today is two-fold. First, in Alaska, we continue to see a one-way ratchet where more and more of our federal OCS is taken off the table, while nothing is done to promote development even where it is needed and supported. Cook Inlet is a good example: instead of working with Alaskans to prevent looming energy shortages in Southcentral, the administration has actively worked against our ability to produce more natural gas from that basin. What we have faced over the past four years is an unbalanced policy that has left us on the verge of importing LNG.

I also object to the manner in which this announcement was made‚Äîpost-election, at the 11th hour, and unilaterally through executive action. These withdrawals are sweeping, limiting the options that future administrations and Congresses have for where our energy should be produced and preventing more thoughtful decisions about what should be made available in each five-year national leasing program.

I understand that President Biden is trying to burnish his environmental legacy, but this is the wrong way to do it.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1953, in his final State of the Union address, President Harry Truman revealed that the United States had successfully developed the hydrogen bomb. 

This announcement came three years after his directive to the Atomic Energy Commission to begin work on the project. Truman's decision was a direct response to the Soviet Union's successful atomic test in 1949, which heightened Cold War tensions and led to fears of a nuclear arms race. The development of the hydrogen bomb marked a significant escalation in the U.S. nuclear arms program, reflecting the growing rivalry between the superpowers. While the U.S. dropped atomic bombs on Hiroshima and Nagasaki in 1945, the hydrogen bomb, which is far more powerful, has never been used in warfare.

Name: Alford, Mark
text:
üö® I‚Äôm proud to serve on the House Appropriations Committee for the 119th Congress.

This critical committee holds a constitutional responsibility: to fund the federal government.

We want to take a moment to explain how the appropriations process works. üßµ‚¨áÔ∏è

Name: Alford, Mark
text:
1/ The Appropriations Committee is divided into 12 subcommittees, each responsible for crafting specific spending bills that fund every corner of the federal government. Here‚Äôs the lineup:

‚Üí Agriculture, Rural Development, FDA: Funds programs supporting farmers, rural communities, and food safety.

‚Üí Commerce, Justice, Science: Funds law enforcement, scientific research, and economic programs.

‚Üí Defense: Oversees funding for our military and national security.

‚Üí Energy and Water Development: Supports energy projects and water infrastructure.

‚Üí Financial Services: Funds the Treasury, IRS, and small business programs.

‚Üí Homeland Security: Ensures our borders and homeland remain secure.

‚Üí Interior and Environment: Manages public lands and environmental protection.

‚Üí Labor, Health and Human Services, Education: Covers critical health, labor, and education initiatives.

‚Üí Legislative Branch: Funds the operations of Congress.

‚Üí Military Construction and Veterans Affairs: Supports military bases and veterans' programs.

‚Üí State and Foreign Operations: Directs foreign aid and diplomatic efforts.

‚Üí Transportation and Housing: Invests in roads, airports, and affordable housing.

Name: Alford, Mark
text: 2/ Each subcommittee drafts a bill specific to its jurisdiction. After hearings and markups, the full Appropriations Committee reviews and votes to send the bill to the House floor.

Name: Alford, Mark
text: 4/ The goal is simple: pass all 12 bills individually to ensure the government runs efficiently and responsibly. Unfortunately, that hasn‚Äôt always been the case in recent years, and Congress has relied too often on last-minute, massive funding packages.

Name: Alford, Mark
text: 3/ Once on the floor, every member of the House debates and votes. If passed, the bill moves to the Senate for their consideration. After both chambers agree on a final version, it heads to the President's desk for signature.

Name: Alford, Mark
